WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.080
Hello everyone, welcome to the Data Scientist Show.

00:00:03.080 --> 00:00:05.680
Today we have Wes McKinney.

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:09.600
He's an open source software developer and entrepreneur focusing on data

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:11.800
processing tools and systems.

00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:14.560
He is the co-creator of Pandas Library,

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:19.160
the author of Python for Data Analysis, which I have a copy of.

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:21.840
And he's the co-founder of Vultron Data.

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:25.480
Currently he's the principal architect at Posit.

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:28.799
He also just launched his MicroVC fund,

00:00:28.799 --> 00:00:32.599
investing in data infrastructure, AI, and ML companies.

00:00:32.599 --> 00:00:35.520
If you like the show, subscribe to the channel,

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:39.639
leave a comment, and give us a five-star review. Welcome to the show, Wes.

00:00:39.639 --> 00:00:41.080
Thanks for having me.

00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:45.480
So I have to ask, what's the backstory of Pandas?

00:00:45.480 --> 00:00:47.840
What was the motivation?

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:51.040
Yeah, well, my first job out of college was in

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:54.560
Quant Finance. I had a math degree, and it was

00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:58.639
2007, and it was the great financial crisis that just started.

00:00:58.639 --> 00:01:03.000
And I was growing frustrated because I was under a lot of pressure to do

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.480
analysis work, and I felt that I wasn't able to do it quickly enough.

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:10.120
And I had been introduced to Python programming, and I said,

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:14.160
hey, this programming language is really great, but it's missing some data

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:17.800
analysis tools, like the kinds of things that I had seen some of my colleagues

00:01:17.800 --> 00:01:21.639
programmed in R. And so I wanted to have some of the same kinds of tools in

00:01:21.639 --> 00:01:25.239
Python that I saw in R. And it was also like a way for me to learn Python and

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:29.400
have exposure to building a software project.

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:31.879
But it started out as tools for myself.

00:01:31.879 --> 00:01:35.959
And at a certain point, I started socializing it with my colleagues.

00:01:35.959 --> 00:01:38.440
And they also really liked using it.

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:42.879
And then I convinced the company where I worked, AQR, to let me open source it.

00:01:42.879 --> 00:01:45.959
And so we open sourced it at the end of 2009.

00:01:45.959 --> 00:01:51.160
And so I gave my first talk to the Python community at PyCon 2010 about the project.

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:52.800
I think that video is still online somewhere.

00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:54.080
You can go see it.

00:01:54.199 --> 00:01:56.400
And yeah, I started grad school in 2010.

00:01:56.400 --> 00:01:59.760
And then at some point, I realized that there was a huge opportunity to make

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:04.080
Python an important language in statistical computing and data science.

00:02:04.080 --> 00:02:09.160
And so I dropped out of grad school to work full-time on Pandas starting from

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:14.960
like May 2011 and spent a little over a year working full-time on the project.

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:17.839
I wrote my book, Python for Data Analysis.

00:02:17.839 --> 00:02:21.479
And yeah, it really helped fill out the features in the library and build the

00:02:21.479 --> 00:02:23.320
initial open source community.

00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:29.320
And sometime in 2013, Changshu and I, he's one of the early developers of Pandas.

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:31.199
He was also at AQR with me.

00:02:31.199 --> 00:02:32.759
We decided to start a company.

00:02:32.759 --> 00:02:36.240
And there were other people that we had gotten involved in Pandas development.

00:02:36.240 --> 00:02:40.479
So when we got busy with our startup, Datapad, we turned over the Pandas project

00:02:40.479 --> 00:02:42.399
to the other core developers.

00:02:42.399 --> 00:02:47.520
So we haven't been so actively involved in Pandas development since like 2013, 2014.

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:51.119
And I've been working on other projects in the meantime, but obviously Pandas has

00:02:51.119 --> 00:02:52.639
become extremely successful.

00:02:52.639 --> 00:02:54.199
And we're all very happy that it exists.

00:02:54.199 --> 00:02:59.119
And it's been a useful tool that's helped the Python data science ecosystem get as

00:02:59.119 --> 00:03:01.360
large and widespread as it is.

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:02.240
Yeah.

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:04.559
And why Pandas?

00:03:04.559 --> 00:03:07.080
I got a lot of questions from my followers.

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:07.759
Yeah.

00:03:07.759 --> 00:03:12.800
So at the time, I spent a lot of time trying to come up with a name because I was

00:03:12.800 --> 00:03:16.119
like, this is a Python data analysis toolkit.

00:03:16.119 --> 00:03:19.759
And I was working with all these econometricians who spent a lot of time

00:03:19.759 --> 00:03:22.000
talking about panel data.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.440
And so I was like, Python data analysis, panel data.

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:29.320
I sort of was mashing around syllables and letters.

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:32.039
And I was like, oh, there's like a panda found in here.

00:03:32.039 --> 00:03:36.199
And so initially it was going to be Panda, but then somebody suggested that

00:03:36.199 --> 00:03:38.639
Pandas was like funnier.

00:03:38.639 --> 00:03:40.559
So that was kind of the backstory.

00:03:40.559 --> 00:03:44.360
But it was, yeah, the main origin of the word was panel data.

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:45.520
And yeah, the name.

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:49.639
Initially, I would say the main challenge was the SEO wasn't good.

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:53.240
You would search for Pandas and you would not get the thing that you were

00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:54.320
looking for.

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:57.160
And eventually, if you wrote Python Pandas, it would come up.

00:03:57.160 --> 00:03:59.399
But now when you type Pandas, it comes up in Google.

00:03:59.399 --> 00:04:00.360
Yeah.

00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:01.399
Cool.

00:04:01.399 --> 00:04:05.679
So basically, all the Python library is just like a zoo.

00:04:05.679 --> 00:04:06.800
Yeah, exactly.

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:12.520
So when you feel frustrated about data processing before you create a Pandas,

00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:17.359
what were some data science or analytics project you were working on?

00:04:17.399 --> 00:04:22.040
Yeah, I was working on a small statistical modeling project that involved some

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:27.320
financial data sets and the data was, was over, it was cross-sectional data over

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:27.720
time.

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:31.359
So panel data and there, the data was patchy.

00:04:31.359 --> 00:04:32.760
So there were some data issues.

00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:36.200
And so I was really the, one of the problems I was really focused on solving

00:04:36.200 --> 00:04:40.679
was making a tool that made it really easy to work with cross-sectional data

00:04:40.679 --> 00:04:41.440
over time.

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:45.440
So time series data or cross-sectional data with a lot of patchiness.

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:50.480
So really good support for the indexing capabilities in Pandas and the, the data

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:55.760
realignment logic that's built into the series and data frame data structure.

00:04:55.760 --> 00:04:58.399
Like I wanted the, all of that to work automatically so that it would like

00:04:58.399 --> 00:05:02.839
automatically deal with the data quality and data alignment issues that I was,

00:05:02.839 --> 00:05:05.000
that I was experiencing in my work.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:09.559
And so it was like trying to incorporate ideas of R, like the data frame data

00:05:09.559 --> 00:05:14.399
structure, the tabular data structure, but also add in the data realignment logic,

00:05:14.399 --> 00:05:15.559
the data indexing logic.

00:05:15.559 --> 00:05:20.640
And so that's why when you use Pandas now, like you have these row index data

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:25.480
structures and column index data structures that assist you in, in, in

00:05:25.480 --> 00:05:26.160
data alignment.

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:30.399
So you can do arithmetic between different time series that have, where maybe a

00:05:30.399 --> 00:05:34.600
time series has different missing dates in one time series or missing, there

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:37.480
might be like missing stock tickers in one, in one series.

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:41.760
And you can do math across these data sets that have data quality issues and

00:05:42.279 --> 00:05:45.640
handles automatically realigning things for you, which is really nice.

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:49.279
But at the time that was, that was like the thing that I really wanted

00:05:49.279 --> 00:05:50.880
to work well and be intuitive.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:51.559
Yeah.

00:05:51.720 --> 00:05:55.720
So after that, you dived into building data processing tools

00:05:55.720 --> 00:05:57.440
and become a software engineer.

00:05:57.640 --> 00:06:01.279
Do you miss the analytics part of things?

00:06:02.119 --> 00:06:07.079
Yeah, I like doing data analysis and statistics and data science work.

00:06:07.119 --> 00:06:10.640
And now, and then I still do, I do a little bit from time to time, but I

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:14.720
haven't, I haven't been a practicing statistician or data scientist in a long

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:15.040
time.

00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:18.760
So really just focusing on infrastructure, software and tools.

00:06:19.119 --> 00:06:21.959
So when I have an opportunity to do some analysis or do some data

00:06:21.959 --> 00:06:23.760
visualization, I always enjoy it a lot.

00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:27.160
Cause I get an opportunity to use the tools that I've built or helped to

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:29.519
build, but yeah, I enjoy building software.

00:06:29.519 --> 00:06:32.679
And yeah, I think it's definitely been, for me, it's been an opportunity to

00:06:32.679 --> 00:06:35.839
build things that have, that have a lot of users and a lot of impact.

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:36.640
Yeah.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:40.079
And what made you want to start Vultron Data?

00:06:40.959 --> 00:06:44.359
So we had spent several years working on Apache Arrow.

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:49.440
So Arrow for people that don't know is, it's a bunch of things, but it started

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:54.040
out, we wanted to create basically a universal table format or a universal

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:58.799
data frame format that could be transported really efficiently between

00:06:58.839 --> 00:07:02.399
data processing systems and between, from one programming language to another.

00:07:02.399 --> 00:07:07.760
So for example, being able to share large datasets efficiently between R and Python.

00:07:08.359 --> 00:07:12.040
And we always had the aspiration of building computing

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:13.640
engines that were Arrow based.

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:17.959
So first we had to get Arrow adopted and successful as a data format and something

00:07:17.959 --> 00:07:19.799
that's adopted and used by many systems.

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:23.679
And then we moved on to building compute engines that are Arrow based.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.959
And so now there's several compute engines that support Arrow

00:07:26.959 --> 00:07:29.359
natively, DuckDB, Data Fusion.

00:07:29.399 --> 00:07:32.320
There's Acero, which is part of the Arrow C++ project.

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:36.799
So we've got these reusable, like mod, we call them modular computing engines.

00:07:37.320 --> 00:07:41.640
And so our idea was that we wanted to create a company that could, on one

00:07:41.640 --> 00:07:46.399
hand, provide a lot of development and commercial support and drive forward

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:51.239
the Arrow development roadmap and provide enterprise support for companies

00:07:51.239 --> 00:07:54.679
that are building on Arrow to be a partner to them in, in helping drive

00:07:54.679 --> 00:07:56.040
forward the open source project.

00:07:56.480 --> 00:08:01.000
But we also saw that there was a lot of opportunity in enabling next generation

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:05.399
data systems to be more modular, to be Arrow based, and to be able to take

00:08:05.399 --> 00:08:07.399
advantage of hardware acceleration.

00:08:07.399 --> 00:08:12.320
So GPUs, but also there's custom Silicon like ASICs being built

00:08:12.359 --> 00:08:13.920
to accelerate data processing.

00:08:14.239 --> 00:08:17.959
And so we recognize that we need to re-architect or help companies

00:08:17.959 --> 00:08:21.440
re-architect their data systems to be able to take advantage of these

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:23.440
advances in computing technologies.

00:08:23.679 --> 00:08:27.519
So we created Voltron Data kind of on one hand to be a driving force in Apache

00:08:27.519 --> 00:08:34.119
Arrow, but also to build some technology to facilitate this transition to these

00:08:34.280 --> 00:08:38.280
kind of modular computing engines and taking advantage of hardware

00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:39.719
acceleration more seamlessly.

00:08:40.119 --> 00:08:45.320
So there'd been a lot of work, initial work, exploratory work, building GPU

00:08:45.320 --> 00:08:49.799
accelerated analytics kernels through the Rapids project at NVIDIA and some

00:08:49.799 --> 00:08:54.359
work on creating accelerated processing engines for Arrow based on the, based

00:08:54.359 --> 00:08:56.520
on Rapids, so the Blazing SQL project.

00:08:56.919 --> 00:09:00.200
And so the company has spent the last, has spent the last almost four years

00:09:00.479 --> 00:09:05.440
working on making that work at scale and in production so that it can be adopted

00:09:05.679 --> 00:09:08.239
amongst large companies running in data centers.

00:09:08.559 --> 00:09:13.520
So, and we have a large team there that over 20 people that work full time on

00:09:13.520 --> 00:09:17.280
open source and have done great things for the Arrow ecosystem and like the

00:09:17.280 --> 00:09:20.679
periphery of projects around Arrow that are helping accelerate

00:09:20.679 --> 00:09:21.960
people's data processing work.

00:09:22.359 --> 00:09:25.640
But Arrow is interesting because it's like the kind of project that most data

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:28.440
scientists won't come into it, into contact with it directly.

00:09:28.440 --> 00:09:31.080
Like it's something that just starts getting used.

00:09:31.080 --> 00:09:34.080
Like it's getting used in Pandas now, it's being used in a lot of other

00:09:34.080 --> 00:09:36.479
projects, but it's used internally.

00:09:36.479 --> 00:09:38.119
So it's something that makes things faster.

00:09:38.119 --> 00:09:40.640
It makes things more efficient, more interoperable.

00:09:40.719 --> 00:09:44.440
Like you can now share data very easily between, between R and Python.

00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:48.080
You can use Arrow to interact with large parquet datasets

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:49.320
that are stored in the cloud.

00:09:49.679 --> 00:09:52.280
So there's all kinds of like new use cases that have been

00:09:52.280 --> 00:09:53.960
unlocked through adoption of Arrow.

00:09:53.960 --> 00:09:56.359
But most data scientists don't need to know about Arrow.

00:09:56.359 --> 00:09:58.880
They just, they get it indirectly through the, the tools

00:09:58.880 --> 00:09:59.840
that they're already using.

00:10:00.119 --> 00:10:00.640
Yeah.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:07.000
So you mentioned modular data processing tools and also your, your investor,

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.320
you're interested in emerging composable data stacks.

00:10:10.599 --> 00:10:15.799
So what's the benefit of the tools being modular or composable?

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:16.200
Yeah.

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:20.559
So the benefit of this, like this modularity or what we call composability

00:10:20.559 --> 00:10:26.880
concept is that it facilitates, it facilitates reuse where firstly, you

00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:31.880
make it easier for people to collaborate on shared, like reusable software

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:34.799
components that, that many people can use to build many different

00:10:34.799 --> 00:10:36.679
kinds of data processing systems.

00:10:37.200 --> 00:10:40.640
And so rather than everybody building a vertically integrated system where

00:10:40.640 --> 00:10:44.599
they're responsible for building all of the constituent pieces of the system,

00:10:44.599 --> 00:10:47.880
instead there's off the shelf components that are high quality, that are state

00:10:47.919 --> 00:10:51.320
of the art that you can use to create a novel data processing system

00:10:51.359 --> 00:10:52.960
using off the shelf components.

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:57.400
And already like DuckDB is a classic example of you have a cutting edge

00:10:57.799 --> 00:11:01.440
analytic database system that's available as a single C++ file that

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:05.239
you can drop into any project, or you can load it into your web application

00:11:05.239 --> 00:11:09.640
and have super fast SQL processing, basically anywhere on your phone and

00:11:09.640 --> 00:11:11.760
your web browser, really anywhere.

00:11:11.840 --> 00:11:16.280
And that reusability and kind of composability is what we call it.

00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:19.479
The composability comes from the use of open standards.

00:11:19.479 --> 00:11:23.080
And so in order to achieve composability, you need to have a standardized

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:26.479
interface between that piece of software and your application.

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:31.520
And so part of what we've done in the Arrow project and in Voltron data is

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:37.599
driving these open standards that enable and facilitate that composability and reuse.

00:11:38.039 --> 00:11:42.400
And so now there's a growing collection of open source projects that are

00:11:42.400 --> 00:11:46.000
participating in what we call the composable data stack.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:50.640
I helped write a paper last year with Meta called the composable

00:11:50.640 --> 00:11:52.599
data management system manifesto.

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:57.320
Try saying that five times fast, but basically we tried to communicate a

00:11:57.320 --> 00:12:02.039
vision for, I guess we can maybe put a link to that paper in the show notes,

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:05.520
but we tried to communicate a vision of what is, what does the future look

00:12:05.520 --> 00:12:09.760
like where data warehouses, databases, and data processing engines are built

00:12:09.760 --> 00:12:12.280
with reusable modular components.

00:12:12.280 --> 00:12:14.640
And the idea is that you want to build a system in such a way that when

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:17.880
something new and better comes up, comes in the future on the horizon,

00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:21.840
that you can change out the old part and put in the new part without disrupting

00:12:21.840 --> 00:12:25.080
the whole user experience so that you get things get better, but you don't

00:12:25.080 --> 00:12:28.280
have to like completely throw out the system and use something completely new.

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:31.400
But you have, yeah, you have something that's you can hot swap components

00:12:31.400 --> 00:12:34.559
without breaking the whole, having to, yeah, throw out the whole system,

00:12:34.559 --> 00:12:36.039
throw out the baby with the bath water.

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:40.960
And yeah, so recently I just launched a venture fund, like a micro venture

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:45.119
fund called composed ventures specifically to invest in companies

00:12:45.119 --> 00:12:46.799
that are helping make this happen.

00:12:47.200 --> 00:12:51.159
And as an entrepreneur, like I've, I've started a company to work, to make

00:12:51.200 --> 00:12:53.400
large contributions to toward this effort.

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:56.400
But now there's a whole ecosystem of companies that are building

00:12:56.400 --> 00:13:01.000
technologies that are helping make it easier to build composable data systems.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:02.359
So it gives me another way.

00:13:02.599 --> 00:13:06.000
And aside from building new projects by investing in companies and helping

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.520
other founders and open source developers, for me, that's another

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:14.080
way that I can help accelerate this transformation of the, the, the data

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:16.080
processing and data science ecosystem.

00:13:16.359 --> 00:13:16.840
Yeah.

00:13:17.039 --> 00:13:21.840
So what do you think is the reason that this composable data stack

00:13:22.239 --> 00:13:24.799
didn't happen, say 10 years ago?

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:26.760
Why now is the right time?

00:13:27.799 --> 00:13:32.320
Yeah, I see it as a natural evolution of the way that systems

00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:33.919
across many domains develop.

00:13:33.919 --> 00:13:38.880
So the best analogy I can give is the, if you look at semiconductor manufacturing,

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:42.000
so the original model of semiconductor manufacturing is the Intel

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:43.919
model, which is vertically integrated.

00:13:43.919 --> 00:13:46.960
So Intel built their own tools.

00:13:47.359 --> 00:13:49.559
All of their designs are proprietary.

00:13:49.599 --> 00:13:52.440
All of their chip fabrication is proprietary and in-house.

00:13:52.440 --> 00:13:56.080
And so like they control everything, everything top to bottom.

00:13:56.520 --> 00:14:02.000
And so compare that to the new kind of the, like the new mod way of designing

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:03.880
and building new computer processors.

00:14:03.919 --> 00:14:07.400
We have open processor architectures and specifications are ones

00:14:07.400 --> 00:14:08.599
that you can license from ARM.

00:14:08.599 --> 00:14:12.919
There's now RISC-V, which is a totally open source, freely available

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:15.840
processor architecture, which can be used for chip fabrication.

00:14:16.159 --> 00:14:19.000
There's different number of companies that build the software

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:20.719
that assists with chip design.

00:14:20.719 --> 00:14:24.320
So Cadence Design Systems is one company that many people have never heard of,

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:27.520
but it's like a very valuable company that builds software for chip design.

00:14:27.919 --> 00:14:32.440
We have fabless, fabless semiconductor manufacturers like NVIDIA, one of the

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:35.159
most valuable companies in the world doesn't own any fabs, like they have

00:14:35.159 --> 00:14:37.960
their chips manufactured by TSMC in Taiwan.

00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:43.760
And so in Taiwan and TSMC by turn has specialized in kind of taking all

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:48.080
of these pieces and being really good at producing with high yield, producing

00:14:48.080 --> 00:14:52.239
chips, but they're dependent on ASML, which provides like the most, the

00:14:52.239 --> 00:14:54.320
world's most advanced photolithography.

00:14:54.599 --> 00:14:59.520
And ASML in Netherlands is also dependent on advanced optics from,

00:14:59.559 --> 00:15:01.239
I think from Zeiss in Germany.

00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:04.640
And so basically what you've had is if you kind of decompose like all of

00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:08.840
these problems that like Intel was responsible from top to bottom, there's

00:15:08.840 --> 00:15:14.400
now like a specialist building these tools with around open specifications

00:15:14.679 --> 00:15:17.880
and kind of reusable systems for each layer of the stacks.

00:15:17.880 --> 00:15:21.239
You've got a specialist in photolithography, a specialist in optics,

00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:25.960
specialist in semiconductor manufacturing, software for chip design.

00:15:26.320 --> 00:15:30.400
And so that's very much like what's going on in data systems right now is

00:15:30.919 --> 00:15:35.119
in the past, it was more expedient for somebody building a database or somebody

00:15:35.119 --> 00:15:39.960
build a data processing system to take ownership of all of the pieces in order

00:15:39.960 --> 00:15:41.679
to ship something more quickly.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:46.080
But now that we've gone through that first wave of progress in open

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:47.599
source data management systems.

00:15:47.599 --> 00:15:50.799
And so now we can start to take a step back and say, okay, well, we want to

00:15:50.799 --> 00:15:53.799
make things 10 times better, but in all of these different places.

00:15:54.239 --> 00:15:58.880
And so there was a collective recognition in the middle 2010s, I would say that it

00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:02.359
wasn't sustainable for us to continue building these vertically integrated

00:16:02.359 --> 00:16:02.840
systems.

00:16:02.840 --> 00:16:08.000
And so that's what led to, well, firstly, there were open source file formats that

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.520
became widely adopted like Parquet, but then Arrow provided this in-memory

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:15.400
computing layer, data interchange and computing layer.

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:17.679
So that everyone realized that was something that we needed.

00:16:18.159 --> 00:16:20.919
Then we need reusable execution engines.

00:16:20.919 --> 00:16:27.440
And so that's led to things like DuckDB, Data Fusion, Velox, so reusable execution

00:16:27.440 --> 00:16:27.919
engines.

00:16:28.119 --> 00:16:32.880
We're starting to think more about the user interface and the query optimization

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:33.239
layer.

00:16:33.239 --> 00:16:37.880
So another project that I created at the same time as Arrow is Ibis.

00:16:37.919 --> 00:16:42.280
It's a Python project, which provides a portable data frame query layer.

00:16:42.280 --> 00:16:47.479
So you can use it to write your analytical queries and then it, depending on what

00:16:47.479 --> 00:16:50.320
backend you're using, whether you're running in memory with DuckDB or with

00:16:50.320 --> 00:16:54.400
pandas, or you're running against your data warehouse, like BigQuery or

00:16:54.440 --> 00:17:01.080
Snowflake or another cloud data warehouse, Ibis knows how to generate the SQL code

00:17:01.119 --> 00:17:04.079
or the pandas operations that you need to run that query.

00:17:04.640 --> 00:17:10.040
And so that really helps with achieving this decoupling of concerns and systems.

00:17:10.439 --> 00:17:14.640
And so, yeah, that was like after building pandas, pandas is an example of a

00:17:14.640 --> 00:17:18.280
vertically integrated project where we were responsible for building everything

00:17:18.280 --> 00:17:18.959
top to bottom.

00:17:18.959 --> 00:17:22.000
And so having gone through that experience already, that was what really

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.640
motivated me, that plus wanting to build Python interfaces to big data systems.

00:17:26.959 --> 00:17:30.520
So when I was at Cloudera, like that was like one of the things that I wanted to

00:17:30.520 --> 00:17:33.520
figure out was like, how do we build Python interfaces that can use all of

00:17:33.520 --> 00:17:38.520
these large scale systems, build Python interfaces that can work with Apache

00:17:38.520 --> 00:17:43.280
Hive or Hadoop or Spark, but not have to rewrite your code to use from one system

00:17:43.280 --> 00:17:43.760
to another.

00:17:43.760 --> 00:17:48.079
So that's what motivated me to create Ibis, which is still going and it's been

00:17:48.079 --> 00:17:52.000
developing rapidly in the last few years, as well as Arrow, which is more of an

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:53.479
infrastructure level project.

00:17:53.479 --> 00:17:58.079
But for Python users, Ibis is a project that you can pick up and use to author

00:17:58.079 --> 00:18:02.079
complex SQL queries and with the comfort of a DataFrame API, which is really nice.

00:18:02.239 --> 00:18:02.719
Yeah.

00:18:02.719 --> 00:18:03.079
Yeah.

00:18:03.319 --> 00:18:10.040
So like you mentioned, pandas is more like vertical and it also has a huge user base.

00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:13.760
So there is a benefit of having a vertical data processing tool.

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:19.439
So when do you think is more appropriate for this vertical type of tools and when

00:18:19.439 --> 00:18:22.319
do you think it's better for composable data tools?

00:18:22.640 --> 00:18:23.079
Yeah.

00:18:23.079 --> 00:18:27.199
So, so one of the challenges with the vertically integrated strategy is that

00:18:27.239 --> 00:18:30.640
especially when you have a piece of software like pandas that people love as

00:18:30.640 --> 00:18:35.119
much as they do, is that they want everything to work just like, work just

00:18:35.119 --> 00:18:35.920
like pandas.

00:18:35.959 --> 00:18:36.280
Yeah.

00:18:36.280 --> 00:18:39.680
And so the trouble is that the pandas API is pretty large.

00:18:40.079 --> 00:18:46.920
And so, and many of the aspects of its API, the code that you write is, is

00:18:46.920 --> 00:18:51.119
coupled to, or it contains details of how pandas is designed and implemented.

00:18:51.640 --> 00:18:55.239
And so if people want to create, and there've been a number of projects like

00:18:55.239 --> 00:19:02.319
Modin, Koalas, that have created pandas emulation layers that translate their

00:19:02.319 --> 00:19:05.160
other operations onto some other execution environment.

00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:10.839
So there's a company Ponder Data, which used Modin to create a pandas interface

00:19:10.839 --> 00:19:11.640
to Snowflake.

00:19:11.920 --> 00:19:15.000
And now they were acquired by Snowflake and are working actively on that in

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:15.560
Snowflake.

00:19:15.959 --> 00:19:20.040
And so the challenge is that you can get 90 or 95% of the way there, but there are

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:24.280
always going to be some, you're never going to be able to totally take existing

00:19:24.280 --> 00:19:28.920
pandas code and run it against another processing engine because there's details

00:19:28.920 --> 00:19:30.800
of pandas that surface in the API.

00:19:31.560 --> 00:19:35.000
And that's, what's very challenging is because whenever you want to swap out the

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:40.959
execution, the storage, if you want to take pandas code and run it at a thousand

00:19:40.959 --> 00:19:46.040
times larger scale on like a large data set, I think Modin and Ponder are designed

00:19:46.040 --> 00:19:50.680
to help with that problem, to be able to run pandas code at scale, but there's

00:19:50.680 --> 00:19:53.599
always going to be some pandas code that it's not going to, that isn't going to be

00:19:53.599 --> 00:19:58.359
able to be translated and run because it's relying on internals, internal

00:19:58.359 --> 00:20:02.599
details of pandas data frame actually contains these NumPy arrays internally.

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:06.680
And so you can get at them through the pandas API and that if you're working on

00:20:06.680 --> 00:20:11.000
an data warehouse or a large cluster, like that's large, like a spark cluster,

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:13.880
like that's not going to work like it does on your laptop.

00:20:14.439 --> 00:20:14.880
Yeah.

00:20:15.079 --> 00:20:19.199
I think for a specific persona, for example, data scientists or machine

00:20:19.199 --> 00:20:25.079
learning engineers, where we have a variety of tools, we're not responsible

00:20:25.079 --> 00:20:26.280
for a large system.

00:20:26.280 --> 00:20:31.079
I think those vertical tools are useful for us to solve a specific problem.

00:20:31.079 --> 00:20:36.239
But if you are building a system to support a variety of use cases.

00:20:36.760 --> 00:20:42.040
I think having portability, particularly at the API level is especially useful for

00:20:42.439 --> 00:20:45.920
like people building systems that need to work in many different environments.

00:20:46.079 --> 00:20:52.199
So for example, with IBIS, like IBIS was designed to give you the power and

00:20:52.239 --> 00:20:56.359
flexibility, like the full power of everything you can do with SQL and SQL

00:20:56.359 --> 00:20:59.680
is a very powerful programming language, which is why it's 50 years old.

00:20:59.719 --> 00:21:02.640
And then like people are still building databases based on SQL.

00:21:03.160 --> 00:21:07.520
So SQL is really powerful, but also SQL dialects are very different

00:21:07.520 --> 00:21:09.079
from database to database.

00:21:09.079 --> 00:21:13.000
Like even though there's the quote unquote SQL standard in practice, like

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:15.599
SQL dialects are different from database to database.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:22.479
And so the idea of IBIS is that you have a single, like a standardized Python API.

00:21:22.479 --> 00:21:23.280
That's data frame.

00:21:23.280 --> 00:21:24.560
That's a real programming language.

00:21:24.560 --> 00:21:25.199
It's Python.

00:21:25.199 --> 00:21:29.520
You get tab completion, you get type checking, like all the nice things that

00:21:29.520 --> 00:21:32.319
you get through Python, the ability to write unit tests, like the ability to

00:21:32.319 --> 00:21:36.079
write functions and reuse code in a modular way, but then at the end of the

00:21:36.079 --> 00:21:41.199
day, you can write code once and then you can run it in any of the 20 different

00:21:41.199 --> 00:21:45.079
backends, or if you're, if you're using multiple types of SQL engines in your

00:21:45.079 --> 00:21:49.439
work, maybe you're using duck DB, but also Databricks SQL or Spark SQL or

00:21:49.439 --> 00:21:53.839
Snowflake or big query from the same Python code, you can get SQL dot, like

00:21:53.839 --> 00:21:57.959
you can emit SQL strings for all of those backends and not have to rewrite

00:21:57.959 --> 00:21:59.839
your code at all, and that is really powerful.

00:22:00.160 --> 00:22:02.880
It's especially powerful for framework developers.

00:22:02.920 --> 00:22:06.520
And so one of the types of projects we, one of the types of projects we've

00:22:06.520 --> 00:22:09.839
been talking to are people that are building like business intelligence

00:22:09.839 --> 00:22:14.199
frameworks or other data analysis frameworks that, that run on top of SQL

00:22:14.199 --> 00:22:16.319
engines for that are written in Python.

00:22:16.719 --> 00:22:22.000
And by delegating the generation of SQL or like creating these complex, complex

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:27.079
SQL strings to IBIS, instead of authoring them by hand is saves people a lot of

00:22:27.079 --> 00:22:27.359
work.

00:22:27.359 --> 00:22:29.839
And so we can centralize that logic in one place.

00:22:30.160 --> 00:22:33.479
There's another project, which is, which IBIS is using now, which is really cool

00:22:33.479 --> 00:22:38.199
called SQL Glot, which is like a SQL dialect transpiler.

00:22:38.599 --> 00:22:41.640
So I don't know if everyone, anyone's had the painful experience of, Oh gosh,

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:44.479
like I've got all these SQL server queries and I need to convert them to

00:22:44.479 --> 00:22:48.479
Postgres or I need to convert them to, to Redshift and like SQL Glot as a tool

00:22:48.479 --> 00:22:49.800
that just built to do that.

00:22:49.800 --> 00:22:50.880
And it's written in Python.

00:22:50.880 --> 00:22:51.199
So.

00:22:51.319 --> 00:22:51.880
Oh, cool.

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:52.119
Yeah.

00:22:52.520 --> 00:22:56.839
I think earlier on, a lot of data processing tools are focusing on

00:22:56.839 --> 00:22:57.839
structured data.

00:22:58.079 --> 00:23:03.239
And now with a larger language models, we have more unstructured data and

00:23:03.239 --> 00:23:04.839
multi-model data.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:10.000
So how do you think that will change the data processing tools?

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:16.079
So multi-modal data is something that we didn't really tackle initially in Arrow.

00:23:16.199 --> 00:23:21.040
And so Changshu, like my co-founder from Datapad and longtime collaborator on

00:23:21.040 --> 00:23:25.359
Pandas and other projects, he recently founded a company called Lance DB.

00:23:25.359 --> 00:23:31.000
And so they are creating the Lance file format, which is an Arrow compatible file

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:34.760
format, but it's designed for multi-modal AI data.

00:23:34.839 --> 00:23:40.680
And so it has support for vector embeddings, images and kind of the data

00:23:40.680 --> 00:23:47.680
that you, you find in, in LLM applications, as well as the indexing kind of building

00:23:47.680 --> 00:23:52.280
the secondary indexes that you need to support LLM, like vector database type

00:23:52.280 --> 00:23:52.880
workloads.

00:23:53.160 --> 00:23:59.319
And we've also seen like a whole ecosystem of new vector database products emerge,

00:23:59.319 --> 00:24:02.439
as well as vector database plugins for existing databases.

00:24:02.439 --> 00:24:05.880
There's, I think a couple of different projects for Postgres, for example.

00:24:06.520 --> 00:24:10.719
It sort of remains to be seen like whether the support for multi-modal data

00:24:10.719 --> 00:24:15.599
where it will happen mainly through specialized tools and systems, as opposed

00:24:15.599 --> 00:24:19.599
to extensions to general purpose databases.

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:24.319
But that's, I think an interesting area to explore, but I think projects like Lance

00:24:24.319 --> 00:24:29.880
that are starting with Arrow and layering on these kind of multi-modal data management

00:24:29.880 --> 00:24:34.719
capabilities are super interesting because it's definitely building for the composable

00:24:34.719 --> 00:24:38.400
data stack by being based on Arrow and using Arrow as much as possible.

00:24:38.800 --> 00:24:43.000
And also using things like Data Fusion, which is kind of an Arrow based Rust

00:24:43.359 --> 00:24:44.119
computing engine.

00:24:44.119 --> 00:24:47.640
It's like a reusable computing engine, which is being used in lots of different

00:24:47.640 --> 00:24:50.560
places as a modular query processing engine.

00:24:50.599 --> 00:24:51.000
Yeah.

00:24:51.400 --> 00:24:56.000
So we see a lot of data tools coming and going.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:01.680
So based on your experience, what are some tools you think are going to be

00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:02.319
obsolete?

00:25:02.319 --> 00:25:06.119
What are some emerging tools you think that are going to be more important?

00:25:06.160 --> 00:25:07.839
I wonder that I might become obsolete.

00:25:07.959 --> 00:25:14.439
Because a lot of us who are writing code, I think the more optimistic way to look at

00:25:14.439 --> 00:25:19.800
it is that we'll get to spend more time doing the fun stuff as co-pilot and

00:25:19.800 --> 00:25:23.119
generative AI, like automates a lot of the boring stuff that we have to do while

00:25:23.119 --> 00:25:28.640
we're doing data analysis or doing CRUD tasks, writing code that's repetitive or

00:25:28.880 --> 00:25:32.239
transforming, forming data from one format to another, things like that.

00:25:32.680 --> 00:25:37.599
I am very optimistic about, yeah, about having better logical separation between

00:25:37.599 --> 00:25:43.119
the APIs and the user interfaces that were used with projects, IBIS, the backend.

00:25:43.160 --> 00:25:46.119
To say that like, not to say that like the Pandas API isn't great.

00:25:46.119 --> 00:25:51.160
Like I think it is great, but it does create, pose a challenge for being able to

00:25:51.520 --> 00:25:57.560
run workloads at scale or to be able to auto essentially transpile your work

00:25:57.560 --> 00:26:01.520
workloads, like based on kind of where you need to run the code and just the size of

00:26:01.520 --> 00:26:03.599
the dataset and many other factors.

00:26:04.199 --> 00:26:08.560
I think this is especially important as we see the hardware, like

00:26:08.560 --> 00:26:10.920
hardware heterogeneity increase.

00:26:11.239 --> 00:26:17.560
So right now, like already we have multiple GPU architectures, like Intel, AMD, and

00:26:17.560 --> 00:26:20.439
Nvidia have separate GPU computing architectures.

00:26:20.439 --> 00:26:24.000
Apple Silicon has its own like metal GPU architecture.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:26.959
And some of the machine learning frameworks have been optimized for all of

00:26:26.959 --> 00:26:28.839
these, for all of these frameworks.

00:26:28.839 --> 00:26:32.160
I think there's a lot of development, like development energy that's involved

00:26:32.160 --> 00:26:36.760
with building support for these different hardware acceleration frameworks.

00:26:36.800 --> 00:26:40.400
I think that as time goes on, it's going to be easier and easier or become

00:26:40.400 --> 00:26:44.479
something that developers have to think less and less about, where basically

00:26:44.479 --> 00:26:49.400
we're able to automatically take advantage of hardware acceleration when it's there

00:26:49.400 --> 00:26:51.680
without having to explicitly opt into it.

00:26:51.920 --> 00:26:55.920
I think that's already happened to, to a great degree in deep learning where like

00:26:55.920 --> 00:27:01.040
with TensorFlow was like a pioneer in enabling hardware heterogeneous computing.

00:27:01.280 --> 00:27:05.560
Try to say that 10 times fast, where you can write your workload in

00:27:05.560 --> 00:27:12.400
TensorFlow or in PyTorch, and if you have TPUs available, it will use them.

00:27:12.400 --> 00:27:14.160
If you have GPUs available, it will use them.

00:27:14.520 --> 00:27:18.160
And so that, that enables portability across, across hardware.

00:27:18.560 --> 00:27:22.520
And so, so that's, I think a really positive, a really positive trend.

00:27:22.560 --> 00:27:27.640
And so I think any increasingly, I think that systems that are not built with this

00:27:27.640 --> 00:27:31.959
modularity in mind and being able to run on different types of hardware seamlessly

00:27:32.280 --> 00:27:36.760
or be reusable or take advantage of these kinds of composable ideas.

00:27:37.040 --> 00:27:39.959
I think those would be increasingly be seen as like the last generation of

00:27:39.959 --> 00:27:44.119
technology that's best replaced by systems that are built for this more like kind of

00:27:44.119 --> 00:27:47.920
modern, the more modern way will be the modular composable way.

00:27:48.199 --> 00:27:52.359
So, and I mentioned, I've been telling everyone I've been following

00:27:52.359 --> 00:27:54.479
pretty actively, this new company modular.

00:27:54.479 --> 00:27:57.359
It's Chris Lattner's, Chris Lattner's new company.

00:27:57.719 --> 00:28:03.000
They, he created the LLVM compiler project and there's a something called MLIR, which

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:08.520
is like a layer on top of that's intended to make it easier to write kernels for deep

00:28:08.520 --> 00:28:12.119
learning or other machine learning workloads, but to be able to compile

00:28:12.119 --> 00:28:13.400
for different hardware targets.

00:28:13.880 --> 00:28:18.599
And so they build a whole new programming language called Mojo for that is producing

00:28:18.599 --> 00:28:21.479
really amazing results on LLM workloads.

00:28:21.479 --> 00:28:26.280
And so I do think that the folks working on compiler technologies that are making it a

00:28:26.280 --> 00:28:27.920
lot easier, the company is called modular.

00:28:27.920 --> 00:28:30.000
So it's like similar theme, right?

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:31.920
To kind of all the things I'm talking about.

00:28:32.199 --> 00:28:35.959
But I think that is like definitely going to be the way, like the way of the future

00:28:35.959 --> 00:28:40.119
in terms of like how we build these systems to create these abstractions where

00:28:40.280 --> 00:28:43.760
developers don't have to really think about the details of the hardware.

00:28:43.760 --> 00:28:47.079
Like nobody will need to be an expert in how NVIDIA GPUs work or

00:28:47.079 --> 00:28:49.119
how Apple Silicon GPUs work.

00:28:49.280 --> 00:28:53.719
That's something that the compiler will take care of and that we'll have expressive

00:28:53.719 --> 00:28:59.839
enough frameworks for developing the systems so that we can generate optimal code that

00:28:59.839 --> 00:29:04.319
runs on each on the type of hardware that's available and that we can upgrade the

00:29:04.319 --> 00:29:06.400
hardware independent of the software.

00:29:06.439 --> 00:29:10.119
And because ultimately what we want, and this was like, this was why we founded

00:29:10.119 --> 00:29:13.839
Voltron data was like, we wanted to create a company that would enable that transition

00:29:13.839 --> 00:29:18.000
to hardware modularity, where you, if the hardware gets better, you can change out

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:20.400
the hardware without disrupting the software experience.

00:29:20.520 --> 00:29:20.800
Yeah.

00:29:20.800 --> 00:29:22.920
But it turns out that getting there is like really hard.

00:29:22.920 --> 00:29:25.160
It takes a lot of money and a lot of engineering work.

00:29:26.239 --> 00:29:26.680
Yeah.

00:29:26.680 --> 00:29:31.920
So what was the biggest challenge when you were at Voltron, when you were building

00:29:31.920 --> 00:29:32.640
the product?

00:29:32.680 --> 00:29:34.520
Well, it's a many layer challenge.

00:29:34.560 --> 00:29:38.040
There's a lot of, cause there's two, so we have a really ambitious vision.

00:29:38.040 --> 00:29:41.119
There's a lot of pieces that need to, they need to fall into place.

00:29:41.160 --> 00:29:44.800
There's open source standards that have to be developed to help.

00:29:45.160 --> 00:29:48.079
I like to help with the contact points between different pieces of the

00:29:48.079 --> 00:29:49.319
stack that we're working on.

00:29:49.640 --> 00:29:55.280
So we recognized that we needed a technology to help connect compute

00:29:55.280 --> 00:30:00.359
engines with the query optimization and front end layers.

00:30:00.359 --> 00:30:04.520
And so we collaborated with a group of people to create the substrate

00:30:04.560 --> 00:30:08.640
project, which has provided, it's even more abstract than even more abstract

00:30:08.640 --> 00:30:12.920
than Arrow, but it's, you can think about it as being like a technology that helps

00:30:12.920 --> 00:30:17.439
connect the language front ends and the query optimization layer with the compute

00:30:17.439 --> 00:30:21.319
engines so that the compute engines don't have to be, it's like, you think it

00:30:21.319 --> 00:30:25.079
wouldn't be optimal for every compute engine have to know how Python works or

00:30:25.079 --> 00:30:28.959
how R works so that it gives you like a standard way of telling the compute

00:30:28.959 --> 00:30:30.199
engine what you want to do.

00:30:30.680 --> 00:30:36.920
But also it creates an abstraction to sort of go from a representation of the

00:30:36.920 --> 00:30:41.119
workload that you want to run to translate that into what physical operations do you

00:30:41.119 --> 00:30:43.239
want to do on the particular hardware that you're using?

00:30:43.880 --> 00:30:48.599
So we not only needed to create like implementations and production ready

00:30:48.599 --> 00:30:52.800
enterprise systems to run real world workloads, like build it in this way, but

00:30:52.800 --> 00:30:56.359
also building the open source standards that make it possible and making sure

00:30:56.359 --> 00:30:59.560
that we aren't over specializing for the particular needs of the company.

00:31:00.040 --> 00:31:03.800
And yeah, I mean, we built 130 person team also during COVID.

00:31:03.839 --> 00:31:08.199
And so raising over a hundred million dollars in venture capital, hiring a

00:31:08.199 --> 00:31:12.599
hundred people all during the pandemic, definitely not for the faint of heart,

00:31:12.640 --> 00:31:16.839
but we had really amazing supportive investors who were big believers in our

00:31:16.839 --> 00:31:17.280
vision.

00:31:17.280 --> 00:31:22.319
And so we were fortunate that we had the support and the capital and the people,

00:31:22.319 --> 00:31:24.560
right, people involved to make it, to make it happen.

00:31:24.760 --> 00:31:25.239
Yeah.

00:31:25.560 --> 00:31:30.800
And later you left Voltron Data and become a principal architect at Posit.

00:31:31.119 --> 00:31:33.319
What made you make this move?

00:31:34.119 --> 00:31:36.359
So I'm still an advisor at Voltron Data.

00:31:36.359 --> 00:31:41.839
So helping out the engineering team and obviously continuing to drive the vision

00:31:41.839 --> 00:31:46.119
around composable data systems and kind of the open source technologies that are

00:31:46.119 --> 00:31:48.319
the foundation of the foundation of the company.

00:31:48.599 --> 00:31:53.239
But after spending between Ursa Labs, Ursa Computing, Voltron Data, I'd spent

00:31:53.239 --> 00:31:56.959
more than five years in entrepreneur mode working on Apache Aero.

00:31:57.280 --> 00:32:01.920
And I'd felt that I had sort of achieved like a lot of what I personally needed to

00:32:01.959 --> 00:32:07.280
contribute to that, contribute to that project and opening myself up to explore

00:32:07.280 --> 00:32:11.880
the ecosystem and look for kind of other projects to make investments in, personal

00:32:11.920 --> 00:32:13.239
investments of time and effort.

