I think that's a really important piece to help with content creation, building

00:34:39.159 --> 00:34:43.800
dashboards, building interactive documents, building interactive applications and

00:34:43.800 --> 00:34:46.000
publishing and sharing results of data analysis.

00:34:46.479 --> 00:34:49.320
So it's, yeah, I'm involved in a bunch of stuff there and yeah, it's an

00:34:49.320 --> 00:34:51.120
amazing team, so I'm very happy.

00:34:51.479 --> 00:34:51.959
Yeah.

00:34:52.320 --> 00:34:57.320
So when you were a full-time co-founder of Ultron Data, did you miss writing

00:34:57.320 --> 00:35:00.239
code and kind of being a creator?

00:35:00.280 --> 00:35:04.600
I would do some coding now and then while it was full-time at Ultron, but you

00:35:04.600 --> 00:35:08.719
know, often, yeah, I guess when you're running a company, often software

00:35:08.719 --> 00:35:10.520
development is not the best use of your time.

00:35:10.520 --> 00:35:15.120
And so sometimes if I would do write some C++ on Arrow, it would usually be like a

00:35:15.120 --> 00:35:18.120
nights and weekends kind of thing, or maybe I had a long plane flight, I'd be

00:35:18.120 --> 00:35:20.199
like, oh, okay, what am I going to do for the next five hours?

00:35:20.199 --> 00:35:20.479
Okay.

00:35:20.479 --> 00:35:23.040
I guess I'll find an issue to hack on and write some code.

00:35:23.080 --> 00:35:26.439
I did miss coding, but I think when you're in that, when you're in an

00:35:26.439 --> 00:35:30.399
operational role like that, I found it's better to, to not get in the way.

00:35:30.439 --> 00:35:33.760
And so I would try not to pick up work that's, that was in the quote critical

00:35:33.760 --> 00:35:37.320
path, because the last thing I'd want is to be like, oh, I have a data hack.

00:35:37.320 --> 00:35:40.000
And then I put up a pull request and the pull request isn't done.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:41.560
And then I get really busy with something else.

00:35:41.560 --> 00:35:44.639
And then there's people who are depending on me to finish this PR and

00:35:44.679 --> 00:35:45.360
that's no good.

00:35:45.360 --> 00:35:46.320
So yeah.

00:35:46.320 --> 00:35:49.679
So I'm happy to be spending more of my time coding again.

00:35:49.679 --> 00:35:53.560
And my plan is to spend the majority of my time doing software development, doing

00:35:53.600 --> 00:35:59.080
direct hands-on coding work or writing, or, you know, beyond podcasts, beyond

00:35:59.080 --> 00:35:59.719
podcasts.

00:35:59.719 --> 00:35:59.959
Yeah.

00:36:00.360 --> 00:36:00.719
Yeah.

00:36:00.719 --> 00:36:07.840
I know a lot of my engineer friends, they later become managers or founders because

00:36:07.919 --> 00:36:12.959
they want to have more impact and then they realize, oh, I miss writing code.

00:36:12.959 --> 00:36:16.199
And now I have to manage people, write performance review.

00:36:16.479 --> 00:36:20.479
And then they really kind of struggle with a change of work.

00:36:20.760 --> 00:36:25.320
And a friend of mine, he was a director of engineering.

00:36:25.399 --> 00:36:29.840
Then later he went back to become an individual contributor.

00:36:30.600 --> 00:36:36.040
He really enjoy, he has more time to write code, but he misses the direct

00:36:36.120 --> 00:36:39.280
influence you can have on your team, on other people's team.

00:36:39.560 --> 00:36:41.159
Do you miss that element?

00:36:41.280 --> 00:36:47.919
I mean, I enjoy doing development work, I think by nature, a change agent.

00:36:47.959 --> 00:36:53.639
And so I think I like building successful software projects, building successful,

00:36:53.919 --> 00:36:55.840
like productive developer groups.

00:36:55.879 --> 00:36:59.840
And so I think that working in an architect role, I think even if you aren't

00:37:00.239 --> 00:37:05.040
directly managing, like directly managing people as an architect, like your job is

00:37:05.040 --> 00:37:09.439
to shape the culture and the roadmap of how the software project works, like the

00:37:09.439 --> 00:37:13.639
tools that it uses, like how it operates on a day-to-day basis, makes decisions.

00:37:13.639 --> 00:37:15.000
Like what is the code review culture?

00:37:15.040 --> 00:37:19.040
What is the issue, like kind of the issue management, like project planning

00:37:19.040 --> 00:37:22.080
culture, as well as identifying like high leverage projects to

00:37:22.080 --> 00:37:24.080
help the project move forward.

00:37:24.600 --> 00:37:28.479
And so I think my most productive periods of being in that principal

00:37:28.479 --> 00:37:31.239
developer role where you're writing a lot of, you're writing a lot of code

00:37:31.239 --> 00:37:34.439
and you're kind of like the tip of the spear, like helping kind of carry the

00:37:34.439 --> 00:37:38.560
torch and lead the charge in an ambitious software project, I really enjoy doing that.

00:37:38.560 --> 00:37:40.239
And I really like working on new things.

00:37:40.600 --> 00:37:42.840
Cause people have asked me like, Wes, like you aren't really working

00:37:42.840 --> 00:37:44.639
on pandas very much anymore.

00:37:44.639 --> 00:37:49.000
And I think partly it's because a lot of the work in pandas is very important.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:50.719
And there's a whole large core team.

00:37:50.919 --> 00:37:52.879
There's pandas is just an enormous project.

00:37:52.879 --> 00:37:56.320
It's had thousands of different people contribute to it, but it's a very

00:37:56.320 --> 00:37:59.280
different project now than it was 15 years ago when it was brand new.

00:37:59.280 --> 00:38:03.840
And so I really enjoy that, like exploratory trailblazing, kind of

00:38:04.120 --> 00:38:07.520
that building something new where you're like figuring, figuring out something

00:38:07.560 --> 00:38:09.360
new, like building something from scratch.

00:38:09.760 --> 00:38:13.479
And usually once a project gets more mature after four or five years,

00:38:13.479 --> 00:38:14.679
this also happened with Arrow.

00:38:14.679 --> 00:38:18.399
Like I'm not doing as much Arrow development these days, but also like

00:38:18.399 --> 00:38:20.919
Arrow has become a more mature software project.

00:38:20.919 --> 00:38:26.080
And so it made sense, like to not be such a looming presence in the project

00:38:26.080 --> 00:38:30.399
and to make space for other maintainers to grow a leadership role in the project

00:38:30.399 --> 00:38:35.000
and to not be dependent on me for kind of driving the project forward, which

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:38.000
is great because it frees me up to think about what to build next.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:41.120
And so that's part of kind of what I'm doing right now is thinking about what's

00:38:41.120 --> 00:38:46.479
next, like where's the, I think Arrow has had a huge impact in the data world.

00:38:46.479 --> 00:38:47.919
Pandas has had a big impact.

00:38:48.239 --> 00:38:51.679
I think Ibis is going to have an even bigger impact in the coming years.

00:38:52.040 --> 00:38:57.320
And so I am looking for other things that we could be doing to help transform,

00:38:57.360 --> 00:39:00.199
kind of transform the ecosystem and continue to make progress.

00:39:00.399 --> 00:39:00.760
Yeah.

00:39:00.760 --> 00:39:06.120
And you're in a very interesting position as a advisor to a startup you founded

00:39:06.120 --> 00:39:12.520
and as a architect posit and you're also investing in a variety of startups.

00:39:12.840 --> 00:39:15.800
So how does your week look like?

00:39:15.919 --> 00:39:19.120
Do you feel you have to constantly change context?

00:39:19.159 --> 00:39:20.280
Well, fortunately, yeah.

00:39:20.320 --> 00:39:23.159
I try to structure my days so that like I have a block of meetings

00:39:23.199 --> 00:39:24.760
and then a block of deep work.

00:39:25.080 --> 00:39:29.879
And so I try to protect as many blocks of, of deep work in my schedule as possible.

00:39:29.879 --> 00:39:33.320
Maybe some of you have read a Paul Graham's essay, the maker's schedule,

00:39:33.320 --> 00:39:37.479
the manager's schedule kind of discusses like the Frick, the push pull between

00:39:37.479 --> 00:39:41.360
having meetings and networking and influencing other people and making

00:39:41.360 --> 00:39:43.639
time for, for doing deep technical work.

00:39:43.959 --> 00:39:48.360
So it's a lot of calendar management and I mentioned I'm doing the venture

00:39:48.360 --> 00:39:51.800
investing, but I'm also trying to not, my goal is not to be a full-time, a

00:39:51.800 --> 00:39:53.919
full-time VC is really a part-time thing.

00:39:53.919 --> 00:39:56.919
And so I'm not out there hustling for hustling for deals.

00:39:56.919 --> 00:40:00.479
If somebody introduces a founder to me or a group of founders to me that are

00:40:00.479 --> 00:40:04.719
working on something where it's something I know about, or I could make a judgment

00:40:04.719 --> 00:40:08.760
about their tech stack or something that seemed that appeals to me, then I'll take

00:40:08.760 --> 00:40:12.560
a look, but yeah, my goal is for venture investing to take as little time as

00:40:12.560 --> 00:40:14.600
possible on the advising front.

00:40:14.639 --> 00:40:15.520
It's an ebb and flow.

00:40:15.560 --> 00:40:15.760
Yeah.

00:40:15.760 --> 00:40:20.000
I think doing podcasts and helping and also networking with other software

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:25.360
developers helps me identify opportunities and ways to create like interesting

00:40:25.360 --> 00:40:28.719
connections, kind of new synapses between these different commercial

00:40:28.719 --> 00:40:29.919
and open source projects.

00:40:30.239 --> 00:40:34.679
So yeah, it's definitely a lot different than it was 10, 12 years ago when I was

00:40:34.679 --> 00:40:38.000
just had just pandas and didn't have a lot going on outside of that.

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:43.800
But I've realized that influencing other people and helping, helping align

00:40:44.120 --> 00:40:48.639
disparate efforts in the open source community, like solving the social

00:40:48.639 --> 00:40:53.360
challenges in open source are, are as important or more important than the

00:40:53.360 --> 00:40:55.280
contributions of any one person.

00:40:55.760 --> 00:40:59.239
And so even when sometimes I'd be like, Oh, it's annoying.

00:40:59.239 --> 00:41:00.120
I have so many meetings.

00:41:00.120 --> 00:41:03.679
I really would rather be coding, but I also have to recognize that like those

00:41:03.679 --> 00:41:07.000
meetings and those conversations, like they are recording podcasts, like they

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:13.879
matter because, um, you know, having people helping, um, get people working

00:41:13.879 --> 00:41:17.919
on thinking on the same wavelength or thinking about things in, in, in

00:41:17.959 --> 00:41:20.679
compatible ways is really important.

00:41:20.719 --> 00:41:24.959
And so like arrow is a good example of a project where, uh, it took a lot of

00:41:24.959 --> 00:41:28.199
collaboration, like a lot of people wrangling to make that project happen.

00:41:28.239 --> 00:41:32.919
But that work of, of getting people like marching to the beat of the same drum,

00:41:33.199 --> 00:41:35.760
it was essential and a project wouldn't have happened otherwise.

00:41:35.800 --> 00:41:40.520
And I think that social labor of understanding what are other people's

00:41:40.520 --> 00:41:43.840
motivations or is there an opportunity to collaborate or could there be something

00:41:43.840 --> 00:41:47.080
we could build that could make collaboration possible?

00:41:47.439 --> 00:41:51.679
That was like, I think for a long time, one of my questions was how do we enable

00:41:51.679 --> 00:41:55.760
the Python and our communities to collaborate and before arrow, like we

00:41:55.760 --> 00:41:59.280
didn't really have a technology that facilitated that collaboration.

00:41:59.280 --> 00:42:02.919
And so now that we have a computing engine and like a whole compute and

00:42:02.919 --> 00:42:06.000
data access framework that ships both in Python and R.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:09.800
So now we can make an improvement to arrow and it's instantly available in

00:42:09.800 --> 00:42:14.360
both Python and R and developers in both eco and both ecosystems can benefit.

00:42:14.360 --> 00:42:14.959
So that's great.

00:42:15.320 --> 00:42:16.399
Yeah, that's awesome.

00:42:16.520 --> 00:42:21.800
Because on social media, people always put Python and R against each other.

00:42:21.800 --> 00:42:26.360
Python and R is like, you have to pick a side and it's great that now in

00:42:26.360 --> 00:42:28.679
positive supports both Python and R.

00:42:29.439 --> 00:42:34.040
Yeah, I think Hadley, Hadley Wickham and I got together back when arrow was

00:42:34.040 --> 00:42:39.040
starting in 2016 and, and talked several times and had said that we thought that

00:42:39.040 --> 00:42:42.360
the quote unquote language wars were kind of dumb and we would just want them to go

00:42:42.360 --> 00:42:42.800
away.

00:42:42.800 --> 00:42:45.919
And so one of the best things that we could do is to start working more

00:42:45.919 --> 00:42:49.040
actively together and building things that could help end the language wars.

00:42:49.040 --> 00:42:51.800
And I think that arrow is one technology that's really helped.

00:42:51.879 --> 00:42:53.040
It's really helped a lot with that.

00:42:53.360 --> 00:42:57.879
And obviously a posit like with its products for data science teams is about

00:42:57.879 --> 00:43:03.000
making it easy for teams that are multi-language to use common technologies,

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:06.439
for example, for report deployment or application deployment.

00:43:06.719 --> 00:43:10.639
So being able to deploy an R based shiny application and a Python based stream

00:43:10.719 --> 00:43:13.399
load application in the same platform is super useful.

00:43:13.639 --> 00:43:17.199
And like being able to deploy an R markdown or a Cordo document or a Jupyter

00:43:17.199 --> 00:43:21.159
notebook and set it up to, I want to send this, rerun this Jupyter notebook and

00:43:21.159 --> 00:43:25.399
send the report to my boss once a week to be able to do that in the same place.

00:43:25.439 --> 00:43:26.199
It's super useful.

00:43:26.199 --> 00:43:30.719
So yeah, I think the polyglot model feels to me like the model of the future.

00:43:30.719 --> 00:43:34.800
And so anybody who's not building for a multilingual environment will find

00:43:34.800 --> 00:43:37.959
themselves kind of disfavored, I think amongst users.

00:43:38.159 --> 00:43:38.760
Yeah.

00:43:39.040 --> 00:43:44.639
And if there's one thing you can change or improve for the open source community,

00:43:44.639 --> 00:43:48.159
it could be cultural or on the technical side, what would that be?

00:43:48.199 --> 00:43:53.399
I mean, I think overall we still need more structured avenues for open source

00:43:53.399 --> 00:43:57.000
developers to get financial support and like direct funding for their work.

00:43:57.120 --> 00:44:00.199
It's definitely, things are a lot better now than they used to be.

00:44:00.199 --> 00:44:02.360
Like there's a number of GitHub sponsors.

00:44:02.360 --> 00:44:06.439
There's a new platform for open source sponsorship called Polar

00:44:06.479 --> 00:44:07.760
that I'm pretty excited about.

00:44:07.760 --> 00:44:09.760
It's different from Polar's, the Python library.

00:44:09.760 --> 00:44:14.080
It's polar.sh, the open source funding platform.

00:44:14.360 --> 00:44:16.719
There's also Tidelift and Patreon.

00:44:17.159 --> 00:44:21.000
So there's new things that we didn't have years ago and there's organizations

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:24.879
like NumFocus that you can donate to that helps get money into the hands of

00:44:24.959 --> 00:44:28.639
funding small projects and infrastructure improvements and open source projects.

00:44:28.639 --> 00:44:32.840
But yeah, I remember a decade ago we had the aspiration of ideally we need a

00:44:32.840 --> 00:44:35.479
hundred million dollars a year of government grants toward open source

00:44:35.479 --> 00:44:37.600
development and we're a long way from that.

00:44:37.679 --> 00:44:41.199
And a hundred million dollars a year wouldn't be enough, I think, to support

00:44:41.199 --> 00:44:44.080
the kind of maintenance and feature development and innovation that's

00:44:44.080 --> 00:44:45.479
needed in this ecosystem.

00:44:45.479 --> 00:44:51.399
And so I think any project that has become dependent on corporate support has

00:44:51.399 --> 00:44:55.560
like an inherent vulnerability because you're in a sense, you're subject

00:44:55.560 --> 00:44:59.159
potentially to the capriciousness of a single, of a company and their ability

00:44:59.159 --> 00:45:01.919
to sustain their investment in that project going forward.

00:45:02.320 --> 00:45:05.679
And so I've heard no project say we have more funding than we know what to do,

00:45:05.679 --> 00:45:08.479
which means I guess the answer is there's not enough funding.

00:45:08.479 --> 00:45:13.719
So I just hope that more corporations can allocate part of their R&D budget

00:45:13.719 --> 00:45:18.719
toward making targeted donations or investments in open source projects

00:45:18.719 --> 00:45:19.439
that they depend on.

00:45:19.800 --> 00:45:20.199
Yeah.

00:45:20.679 --> 00:45:25.679
And you said you like to work on new things and when you face a lot of new

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:31.199
options, what's your philosophy or do you have a set of criteria when you want

00:45:31.199 --> 00:45:32.800
to decide what to work on next?

00:45:32.840 --> 00:45:34.840
I try to learn from the users.

00:45:34.840 --> 00:45:39.520
I listen, or if I, if I'm building something myself, if I find that

00:45:39.639 --> 00:45:42.600
something doesn't work quite the way that I think it should, then I'll try to

00:45:42.600 --> 00:45:45.280
like talk to other people and see, is this a problem that you also think

00:45:45.280 --> 00:45:46.679
that this doesn't seem great.

00:45:46.679 --> 00:45:48.120
Do you also think this is a problem?

00:45:48.120 --> 00:45:52.080
And so, I mean, that's basically what happened with, with Arrow is that I had

00:45:52.080 --> 00:45:56.040
a suspicion that there was a problem to be solved, but it took the better part

00:45:56.040 --> 00:45:59.800
of a year till I find other people that had thought about, had the

00:45:59.800 --> 00:46:01.239
same ideas had occurred to them.

00:46:01.719 --> 00:46:03.600
And then we had to convince each other, can I work with you?

00:46:03.600 --> 00:46:04.360
Can I work with you?

00:46:04.399 --> 00:46:07.879
And so we, we got a coalition of people together to start working on a project,

00:46:07.919 --> 00:46:13.040
but yeah, I think I trust my intuition like a lot in terms of what to spend my

00:46:13.040 --> 00:46:17.840
time on, but I definitely do collect feedback and try to get market research,

00:46:17.879 --> 00:46:22.199
talk to real users and confirm, you know, confirm my hunches about what

00:46:22.199 --> 00:46:23.439
problems are worth working on.

00:46:23.639 --> 00:46:24.120
Yeah.

00:46:24.560 --> 00:46:28.000
And what are something you are learning right now?

00:46:28.040 --> 00:46:32.159
I'm learning Rust and like a lot of people, maybe later than a lot of people,

00:46:32.159 --> 00:46:35.959
but I think there's a lot of like new Rust based tools that are coming

00:46:35.959 --> 00:46:37.639
out in the Python ecosystem.

00:46:37.719 --> 00:46:41.639
And I'm an investor in Astral, which is the company behind the

00:46:41.639 --> 00:46:43.719
rough code formatter and linter.

00:46:43.800 --> 00:46:48.320
And also they just released a new PIP replacement called UV, which is like a

00:46:48.399 --> 00:46:50.800
ultra fast kind of package management tool.

00:46:51.399 --> 00:46:52.800
And that's all implemented in Rust.

00:46:53.239 --> 00:46:57.439
And so I'm pretty excited about the use of making it easier to develop Python

00:46:57.439 --> 00:47:01.280
extensions and to do more systems programming and address some of the

00:47:01.280 --> 00:47:02.639
shortcomings of Python.

00:47:02.919 --> 00:47:06.760
I also think it's great that Guido van Rosum is at Microsoft and is working

00:47:06.760 --> 00:47:08.399
on making CPython faster.

00:47:08.719 --> 00:47:12.520
I kind of gave some feedback also to Microsoft about their Python and Excel

00:47:12.520 --> 00:47:13.199
integration.

00:47:13.199 --> 00:47:15.320
And so I think that's all super cool.

00:47:15.479 --> 00:47:19.080
So yeah, I'm still continuing to expand my repertoire of skills.

00:47:19.080 --> 00:47:21.879
And, and yeah, as I mentioned, I'm doing some little bit of TypeScript

00:47:21.879 --> 00:47:26.600
development cause I'm interested in using DuckDB compiled to WebAssembly to do

00:47:26.600 --> 00:47:27.080
things.

00:47:27.479 --> 00:47:29.760
And that's all, it's some really cool stuff there.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:34.120
And yeah, cause in the past, our company Datapad, we built a visual analytics

00:47:34.120 --> 00:47:37.520
product, but we had to build a whole data processing engine to power it.

00:47:37.520 --> 00:47:39.879
And nowadays you could just use DuckDB to do that.

00:47:40.199 --> 00:47:44.159
And so we have all these like nice tools that didn't exist a decade ago.

00:47:44.159 --> 00:47:47.600
And so I'm exploring and thinking about things that ways that they could be

00:47:47.600 --> 00:47:51.959
incorporated to, to level up the experience of, for data scientists.

00:47:52.120 --> 00:47:52.520
Yeah.

00:47:52.760 --> 00:47:58.679
So before we Red Pop, what is something you were excited about in your career or

00:47:58.879 --> 00:47:59.719
personal life?

00:47:59.760 --> 00:48:02.679
Well, aside from all the things that we've been talking about, which I'm

00:48:02.679 --> 00:48:05.919
definitely excited about outside of programming, I like foreign languages.

00:48:05.919 --> 00:48:07.760
And so it's been a lot of time on language learning.

00:48:07.760 --> 00:48:11.199
So it's like I'm learning French and Italian right now, which I enjoy a lot.

00:48:11.560 --> 00:48:15.679
And like the tools and things for learning language learning have become so much

00:48:15.679 --> 00:48:16.120
better.

00:48:16.120 --> 00:48:19.760
And that not only is there like ton of amazing content on the internet, on

00:48:19.760 --> 00:48:24.399
YouTube and podcasts, but also using ChatGPT for language learning is

00:48:24.399 --> 00:48:25.520
tremendously useful.

00:48:25.560 --> 00:48:26.199
And so

00:48:26.280 --> 00:48:28.479
how do you use ChatGPT for language learning?

00:48:28.600 --> 00:48:33.239
As you can imagine, it's really good at translating idiomatic ideas, or if you

00:48:33.239 --> 00:48:37.360
ask it for like examples of how to say different things, but also how to say

00:48:37.360 --> 00:48:40.959
different things, like in different contexts of like, how formal is the

00:48:40.959 --> 00:48:41.959
situation you're in?

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:44.800
What would you say to like your family or your friends versus what would you say

00:48:44.800 --> 00:48:47.159
to somebody you're doing business with somebody you don't know?

00:48:47.159 --> 00:48:49.719
And so, yeah, I found it tremendously useful.

00:48:49.919 --> 00:48:53.800
Also for, you could tell it to like, take an article that's written in one

00:48:53.800 --> 00:48:57.280
language, say, I want you to translate this, but generate a summary of it in a

00:48:57.280 --> 00:48:58.080
different language.

00:48:58.479 --> 00:49:03.639
And so if you're interested in like, how would you express like complex ideas or

00:49:03.639 --> 00:49:08.679
ideas that you don't necessarily have the linguistic capability to express, but it

00:49:08.679 --> 00:49:12.399
can assist you in putting something into words and then you see, okay, well, how

00:49:12.399 --> 00:49:14.560
would ChatGPT say this in my target language?

00:49:14.560 --> 00:49:18.159
And so it's super useful for generating novel content.

00:49:18.399 --> 00:49:18.800
Yeah.

00:49:18.840 --> 00:49:24.679
Have you used ChatGPT to help you learn Rust or in other software development

00:49:24.760 --> 00:49:25.360
process?

00:49:25.760 --> 00:49:26.439
I've used it.

00:49:26.479 --> 00:49:33.280
I've used GPT, mainly GPT-4 for writing tedious scripts.

00:49:33.320 --> 00:49:37.000
Things, most recently I used it to do some things with the GitHub API.

00:49:37.360 --> 00:49:38.399
And I was like, yeah, okay.

00:49:38.399 --> 00:49:41.040
I could read the GitHub API and figure out how to do this on my own.

00:49:41.040 --> 00:49:45.399
And I know how to use requests and I know how to do, reuse Rust APIs and stuff.

00:49:45.399 --> 00:49:51.000
But ChatGPT knows all of that too, and has an encyclopedic knowledge of the GitHub

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:52.199
documentation and everything.

00:49:52.199 --> 00:49:56.600
So you can ask it to write Python code for you to do pretty much any task that you

00:49:56.600 --> 00:50:00.760
want and you'll have the results in seconds rather than having to pour through the API

00:50:00.760 --> 00:50:02.479
documentation and figure it out yourself.

00:50:02.520 --> 00:50:07.760
I think that to me is like to eliminate a lot of the drudgery associated with being

00:50:07.760 --> 00:50:11.760
a software developer and not having to spend time on boring, but straightforward

00:50:11.760 --> 00:50:16.120
tasks, definitely as a good use case for, for LLMs and things like Copilot.

00:50:16.280 --> 00:50:17.520
I still haven't set up Copilot.

00:50:17.560 --> 00:50:21.239
I've got to figure out how to hook up Copilot with Emacs since I'm an Emacs

00:50:21.239 --> 00:50:23.040
user, but I'll work on that.

00:50:23.280 --> 00:50:23.679
Yeah.

00:50:23.919 --> 00:50:31.439
So say after 20 years, what kind of impact do you want to leave for the community?

00:50:31.479 --> 00:50:36.040
I think, I mean, in general, like I'm really interested in continued growth

00:50:36.080 --> 00:50:37.800
of like open source data science.

00:50:37.840 --> 00:50:41.719
I think that one of the reasons that one of the main reasons I'm at Posit is because

00:50:41.719 --> 00:50:46.479
I think they've built one of the most sustainable businesses that is largely

00:50:46.520 --> 00:50:48.239
open source data science focused.

00:50:48.479 --> 00:50:52.679
Huge fraction, I don't know the exact numbers, but like a significant fraction

00:50:52.679 --> 00:50:56.800
of the engineering team works on works primarily on open source projects.

00:50:57.239 --> 00:51:02.879
And so I think the, and JJ, the CEO and founder, he has the aspiration of

00:51:02.879 --> 00:51:06.360
building a hundred year company that can survive him and survive all of us.

00:51:06.719 --> 00:51:12.439
And so I think given how passionate I am about solving the open source

00:51:12.439 --> 00:51:16.679
funding and sustainability dilemma, that if we, I, if I can help do that by

00:51:16.719 --> 00:51:22.320
building, my building Posit's business and helping the company grow its impact

00:51:22.320 --> 00:51:27.919
and achieve a, if be operating in terms of impact at 10 times the scale that it

00:51:27.919 --> 00:51:33.199
is now in terms of the contributions to open source and its footprint in how

00:51:33.199 --> 00:51:36.320
people do data science and in the business context, that would be very

00:51:36.320 --> 00:51:39.760
satisfying to me because it serves my goals of building impactful open source

00:51:39.760 --> 00:51:43.159
projects, but also doing it in a sustainable way and increasing.

00:51:43.520 --> 00:51:47.120
I've had the opportunity to direct a lot of commercial funding

00:51:47.120 --> 00:51:48.439
into open source development.

00:51:48.439 --> 00:51:49.280
And I like doing that.

00:51:49.280 --> 00:51:54.080
And I, to have a large team and being able to contribute in a major way, what

00:51:54.080 --> 00:51:56.760
we've been able to do with Arrow development has been, has been really

00:51:56.760 --> 00:51:57.639
satisfying to me.

00:51:57.639 --> 00:52:01.800
And so to continue doing that and to be able to do that at an even larger

00:52:01.800 --> 00:52:05.719
scale is a, is definitely a major goal for me for the rest of my career.

00:52:06.040 --> 00:52:06.360
Yeah.

00:52:06.760 --> 00:52:11.560
Well, thanks Wes for coming to the show and I'm excited to see the growth of

00:52:11.560 --> 00:52:12.959
Posit and your work.

00:52:13.639 --> 00:52:14.080
Thank you.

00:52:14.120 --> 00:52:14.840
Thanks for having me.

